In the [[mathematics|mathematical]] discipline of [[graph theory]], a subset of vertices in a [[Graph (discrete mathematics)|graph]] ''G'' is called '''dissociation''' if it induces a subgraph with maximum degree 1. The number of vertices in a maximum cardinality dissociation set in ''G'' is called the '''dissociation number''' of ''G'', denoted by diss(''G''). The problem of computing diss(''G'') (dissociation number problem) was firstly studied by [[Mihalis Yannakakis|Yannakakis]].<ref>{{harvnb|Yannakakis|1981}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Papadimitriou and Yannakakis|1982}}</ref> The problem is [[NP-hard]] even in the class of [[Bipartite graph|bipartite]] and [[planar graph]]s.<ref>{{harvnb|Yannakakis|1981}}</ref>
