{{Infobox person |name = Nate Ackerman |image = Nate Ackerman.jpg |alt = |caption = |birth_date = {{Birth date|1978|03|04}} |birth_place = New York City, New York |death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> |death_place = |other_names = Nathanael Leedom Ackerman |known_for = Olympic and World Championship wrestler |occupation = Lecturer in mathematics at [[Harvard University]] |nationality = British and American<ref name=Burnett/> }}
'''Nate Ackerman''' (born March 4, 1978 as '''Nathanael Leedom Ackerman''') is a [[United Kingdom|British]]-[[United States|American]] [[mathematician]] and [[Wrestling|wrestler]]. He is the son of [[Peter Ackerman]] and [[Joanne Leedom-Ackerman]].
Ackerman competed in the [[2004 Summer Olympics|2004 Summer Olympic Games]] as part of the [[Great Britain at the 2004 Summer Olympics|Great Britain National Team]].<ref name=Guardian>{{cite web |last=Phillips |first=Michael |title=Britain's only wrestler grapples with a crowd |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2004/may/25/athensolympics2004.olympicgames |date=25 May 2004 |work=Athens 2004 |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=14 July 2009}}</ref> He also competed in the [[1999 World Wrestling Championships|1999]], [[2001 World Wrestling Championships|2001]], 2002, 2003, 2005 and 2011 World Championships.<ref>[https://www.iat.uni-leipzig.de/datenbanken/dbfoeldeak/daten.php?spid=B71507360C794F80AB78E0C16401D490 Ackerman, Nathanael Leedon (GBR)]. FILA Wrestling Database. Retrieved on 20 July 2009.</ref> Ackerman's best international finish was 10th at the 2002 Commonwealth Games.<ref name=Burnett>{{cite web |last=Burnett |first=Mike |title=Road to Athens: Nate Ackerman |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympics_2004/wrestling/3911451.stm |date=28 July 2004 |work=Olympics 2004 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=14 July 2009}}</ref>
Ackerman was born in [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]] to [[Joanne Leedom-Ackerman]] and [[Peter Ackerman]]. He was educated at the [[American School in London]]<ref>{{citation|title=MIT brains, brawn and bright lights go to Athens Olympics|journal=MIT News|publisher=[[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]]|url=http://newsoffice.mit.edu/2004/olympics|first=Denise|last=Brehm|date=August 13, 2004}}</ref> and then [[Harvard University]], where he graduated in June 2000. He received his [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] in mathematics in 2006 from [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]].<ref>{{mathGenealogy|98770}}</ref><ref>{{cite thesis | type=Ph.D. thesis | url=http://www.math.harvard.edu/~nate/papers/misc/thesis/thesis.pdf | author=Nathanael Leedom Ackerman | title=On Quantifier Rank Spectrum of L-Infinity-Omega | institution=Massachusetts Institute of Technology | year=2006 }}</ref> He is currently a lecturer in mathematics at [[Harvard University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Harvard Mathematics Department : Visitors and Postdocs |url=http://math.harvard.edu/people/visitor.html |publisher=Harvard University |accessdate=March 31, 2015}}</ref>
