{{short description|German-Jewish mathematician}} {{Infobox scientist | name = Ludwig Otto Blumenthal | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = Plaucherel Goldziher Blumenthal Zurich1932.tif | image_size = | alt = | caption = ''Left to right, standing:'' [[Michel Plancherel]], Prof. Karl Goldziher (Budapest), Otto Blumenthal, ''sitting:'' Ms. Blumenthal, and an unknown woman, at the [[International Mathematical Congress]], Zürich 1932 | birth_date = {{birth date|1876|7|20|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Frankfurt]], [[Hesse-Nassau]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1944|11|12|1876|7|20|df=y}} | death_place = [[Theresienstadt concentration camp]] | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!--{{coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}--> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = | workplaces = | patrons = | education = | alma_mater = [[Göttingen University]] | thesis_title = Über die Entwicklung einer willkürlichen Funktion nach den Nennern des Kettenbruches <math>\scriptstyle \int_{-\infty}^0 (z - \xi)^{-1} \varphi(\xi) d\xi</math> | thesis_url = <!--(or | thesis1_url = and | thesis2_url = )--> | thesis_year = 1898 | doctoral_advisor = [[David Hilbert]] | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = [[Karl Gehlen]] | notable_students = | known_for = Editor of ''[[Mathematische Annalen]]'', 1906-1938 | influences = | influenced = | awards = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | spouse = Mali Ebstein | partner = <!--(or | partners = )--> | children = Margrete (born 1911), Ernst (born 1914) | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!--{{URL|www.example.com}}--> | footnotes = }}
'''Ludwig Otto Blumenthal''' (20 July 1876 – 12 November 1944) was a [[Germany|German]] [[mathematician]] and professor at [[RWTH Aachen University]].
==Biography== He was born in [[Frankfurt]], [[Hesse-Nassau]]. A student of [[David Hilbert]], Blumenthal was an editor of ''[[Mathematische Annalen]]''. When the [[Law for the Restoration of the Professional Civil Service|Civil Service Act of 1933]] became law in 1933, after [[Enabling Act of 1933|Hitler became Chancellor]], Blumenthal was dismissed from his position at [[RWTH Aachen University]].<ref>{{Cite book| publisher = BRILL| isbn = 978-90-04-29639-8| title = Voices from Exile: Essays in Memory of Hamish Ritchie| date = 2015-06-05|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ybG9CwAAQBAJ&pg=PA124}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book| publisher = Cambridge University Press| isbn = 978-1-107-00684-3| last1 = Hoffmann| first1 = Dieter| last2 = Walker| first2 = Mark| title = The German Physical Society in the Third Reich: Physicists Between Autonomy and Accommodation| date = 2012 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7hH8BXyl7gEC&pg=PA248}}</ref>
Blumenthal, who was of Jewish background, emigrated from the Nazis to the Netherlands, lived in [[Utrecht]] and was deported via [[Westerbork transit camp|Westerbork]] to the [[nazi concentration camps|concentration camp]], [[Concentration camp Theresienstadt|Theresienstadt]] in [[Bohemia]] (now [[Czech Republic]]), where he died.
In 1913, Blumenthal made a fundamental, though often overlooked, contribution to aerodynamics by building on [[Nikolay Yegorovich Zhukovsky|Joukowsky's]] work to extract the [[complex number|complex]] transformation that carries the latter's name,<ref>[https://ntrs.nasa.gov/archive/nasa/casi.ntrs.nasa.gov/19930090787_1993090787.pdf]</ref> making it an example of [[Stigler's Law]].
